si.t: The Contacts sheet should be used to store the data that will be used in the emails you're sending.

When you want to make a new email message, you do that in the Messages sheet. You first pick a keyword, then write a subject and body, then pick how many days you want to follow up on that email message. The Subject and Body can contain variables, the other columns cannot.
These instructions are in no particular order. The instructions in A2 and B2 probably have nothing to do with each other. This is true for every instruction in every row
SPACING MATTERS!!! "Follow Up" does not equal "FollowUp" "status" does not equal "status "

r.t: The headers can be in any order you want (even the required ones), but there
can't be gaps
between the headers, they must all be
continuous

si.t: The Messages sheet should be used to hold the data that determines what to do for a given row within the contacts sheet.

r.t: You
can't
change the headers in the Messages sheet. They must be in the order I put them in.
Keyword

: Say you wrote an email message out in the Messages sheet, and you named the keyword "Status", if you put "Status" as the keyword in some row(s) in the Contact sheet, you will send the "Status" message to those people. The spelling of the keyword
MUST
exactly match the way it is spelled in Messages, capitalization matters.
Email
: this is the email address of the contact in a given row. Make sure it is written correctly or the program will crash sometimes.
Keyword

: This is the term that corresponds to the message you want to send. If you put the keyword "Inquiry" in a row in the Messages sheet, then some row(s) contain "Inquiry" as the keyword, the message on the row that has the "Inquiry" keyword in Messages will be sent to that contact(s).
Last Contacted
: When an email is sent to a contact, this value will automatically update to today's date. You don't need to fill this out.
Follow Up

: When an email is sent to a contact, this value will automatically update to today's date + the number in the Follow Up Days slot in Messages corresponding to the keyword used. You don't need to fill this out.
Follow Up Days

: This is the number of days you want to wait before following up on this specific email message. It will mark the Follow Up value in the Contacts sheet accordingly. The sheet won't automatically follow up on that day, it only marks when you should follow up for your own records. If you want to follow up with them in a week, put a 7 in this cell. There is no "1 month" you have to write "30" or "31". If you leave this slot blank, it should make the Follow Up date today.
Subject
: This is the subject of the email for a given message.
It can contain variables

. Variables are parts of the subject/body that are specific to the contact. For example, you may want to include somebody's company name in the subject of the email you send them, that company name would be a variable. See cell
B9
Body
: This is the body of the email for a given message.
It can contain variables
. You will also want to use line breaks in your email body, this is explained in cell
C3
of this Instructions sheet. Keep in mind there will automatically be space after the email body and you're signature, so you shouldn't put line breaks at the bottom of your email body. See cell B9.
VARIABLES EXPLAINED

: To include a variable in an email Subject and/or Body, you have to use the "~" symbol (its at the top left of the keyboard). The way you use a variable is as follows: Hi ~Name~, This variable would have to correspond exactly to a header in your contacts sheet; meaning if you use a variable in your message, it must be a header in your Contacts sheet. They must be spelled, capitalized, and spaced
EXACTLY THE SAME WAY

or the variable won't work properly and the code may crash. In the example I showed here, if you have a row with the Name set to "Mason", the email that corresponds to this example would say "Hi Mason,". You can include as many or as few variables as you'd like, they can be in any order you want. Just because you include a variable header in your Contacts sheet doesn't mean it needs to be in an email subject/body. Variables are the most particular part of the program, so if you cannot figure them out, please read this section again, if you still don't understand, ask Mason or anyone in the office who does understand.

si.t: If a header is bolded, that means you shouldn't touch it, change it, or delete it. The bolded headers are all required to make the program function properly.
When you make a new email message, it may not send the way you expected it to when you wrote it up. Please test an email message whenever you write/change it before sending it out to clients.

Once you've set up you list of contacts and the messages you want to send to them, assuming you already tested your new message, you will have to run the "Send" macro to start the email blast. Press CTRL+SHIFT+S to start the email blast. The program will send an email to the email address in every row of the Contacts sheet until it reaches an entirely blank row. If one row has some keyword, and the next row has a different keyword, and another row has the first keyword, it will send the correct email messages that correspond with those keywords. Think of each row as it's own process separate from the other rows.

r.t: If you run the "Send" macro on a list, then run it again right after, it will send the same emails to those same contacts right away.
If you don't want to send someone an email, remove them from this sheet
Sending Email Address:

This value determines which email address you will be sending an email FROM. You can only use an email address that you have access to on the computer you are running this program on. If the email address shows up as one of the email addresses on the left bar of your Outlook, that means you have access to it. You MUST fill this out for each row you include in the Contacts sheet. DO NOT EVER leave it blank. Also, if you send somebody an email using a given Sending Email Address, DO NOT EVER change that Sending Email Address for that given row. It will cause massive problems.

si.t: This email blaster can now send replies be sure to re-read the instructions if you used this sheet before it was able to send replies.

When writing your email body in a cell and you want to make a new line, press ALT+ENTER. It should make a new line like this. If you want multiple new lines (which is common in emails" press it multiple times.
And it'll look like this.

I know these instructions are lengthy, that's because they are very detailed. They are meant to teach you everything you need to know about this program so that you don't make a mistake and send 1000 emails to the wrong people or cause your computer to crash or something. Even though they are long, I highly encourage you to read every instruction on this sheet.

When building an email that is meant to be a reply, the Subject is very important. The subject will be used to find the correct email chain. So if you have and Inquiry email, and an Inquiry Follow Up email reply, make sure the subjects are the same in the Messages tab.

r.t: The column headers in Contacts can be whatever you want them to be, but you
MUST
also have the following headers: Full Name Email, Keyword, Last Contacted, Follow Up, Sending Email Address. These essential header names must be spelled
exactly
how they're spelled here, capitalization matters.
Full Name:

You only need to put a contact's full name if you plan on sending a follow up email. Note that this full name will not provide any data towards the email body or subject, so if you want to include somebody's name in an email body, that has to be it's own variable.
Next Keyword:

This is the keyword you want the contact to be set to once you send a given email. If I send someone an "Inquiry" keyword email, then I want the follow up email I send to them to be the "Follow Up" keyword email, I would put "Follow Up" in the Next Keyword column of the message with the "Inquiry" keyword.
New Email or Reply?:

This determines whether an email message is meant to be a new email or a reply to an existing email chain. You have two options for values in this column: New Email or Reply. DO NOT put anything else. DO NOT leave this value blank for a given row. Note that if you choose Reply, the email sent with that corresponding message will find the email chain of the contact, check if that person responded, if they didn't, it will end the message. If they did respond, the program will mark the Keyword of that column with a "*" before the Keyword. In the case that the recipient has already responded in this email chain, the Keyword of that column will be marked with a "#" before the Keyword. If either of these 2 exceptions happens, the keyword will not be updated to the next keyword.
